c0=A.iZ("High-frequency UPSC topic. Tests understanding of constitutional interpretation, fundamental rights expansion, and digital governance. Expected in both Prelims and Mains GS-II.","",c1,"","In one of the most significant constitutional rulings in recent decades, the Supreme Court of India delivered a landmark judgment affirming that the Right to Privacy is a fundamental right protected under Article 21 (Right to Life and Personal Liberty) of the Indian Constitution.\n\nThe nine-judge Constitution Bench unanimously held that privacy is intrinsic to life and liberty and that it encompasses bodily autonomy, informational privacy, and the privacy of choice. Justice D.Y. Chandrachud, writing the lead opinion, stated that privacy is essential for the exercise of other fundamental freedoms.\n\nThe ruling establishes that any government action impacting privacy must satisfy a three-part test:\n1. Legality \u2014 there must be a law authorizing such action\n2. Necessity \u2014 the state must demonstrate a legitimate aim\n3. Proportionality \u2014 the means must be proportionate to the objective\n\nThis judgment has wide implications for:\n- The Digital Personal Data Protection Act, 2023\n- Aadhaar-linked services and biometric data collection\n- Government surveillance programs\n- Data localization policies under the upcoming Digital India Act\n- Right to be forgotten in digital spaces\n\nThe ruling overruled two earlier judgments \u2014 M.P. Sharma (1954) and Kharak Singh (1962) \u2014 which had held that privacy was not a guaranteed right under the Constitution.","",b,A.a(["Constitutional question raised","9-judge bench constituted","Arguments on Art. 21 scope","Unanimous ruling: Privacy is fundamental","3-part test established for government interference","Overruled M.P. Sharma & Kharak Singh","Framework for DPDP Act & future legislation"],b8),"","a2","https://picsum.photos/seed/supreme_court_india/800/400",!0,c3,B.bW,"PRIVACY: P=Puttaswamy, R=Right to Life (Art.21), I=Informational privacy, V=Validity test (3-part), A=Autonomy (bodily), C=Choice privacy, Y=Yesterday's cases overruled",a2,B.ag,b9,q,c0,"","A nine-judge Constitution Bench unanimously ruled that the Right to Privacy is a fundamental right under Article 21, with far-reaching implications for data protection and governance.","","Supreme Court Landmark: Right to Privacy in the Digital Age",a3)
