p=A.iZ("Frequently tested in Prelims and Mains. Understand cap-and-trade vs carbon tax, role of BEE, and how CCCs work. Link to India's updated NDCs.","",o,"","The Ministry of Environment, Forest and Climate Change has launched India's first comprehensive Carbon Credit Trading Scheme (CCTS), establishing a market-based mechanism for industries to trade carbon credits and reduce greenhouse gas emissions.\n\nHow the Scheme Works:\n1. The government sets emission intensity benchmarks for obligated industries\n2. Industries performing better than benchmarks earn Carbon Credit Certificates (CCCs)\n3. Industries unable to meet targets must purchase CCCs from the market\n4. The trading creates a financial incentive for cleaner production\n\nInstitutional Framework:\n\u2022 Bureau of Energy Efficiency (BEE): Designated as the administrator\n\u2022 Indian Carbon Market (ICM): The trading platform\n\u2022 The Grid Controller of India: Provides emission data from the power sector\n\u2022 Central Electricity Regulatory Commission (CERC): Approves market procedures\n\nIndia's Climate Targets:\nThe scheme aligns with India's updated Nationally Determined Contributions (NDCs) under the Paris Agreement:\n- 45% reduction in emission intensity of GDP by 2030 (from 2005 levels)\n- 50% cumulative electric power from non-fossil fuel-based energy resources by 2030\n- Net-zero emissions by 2070\n\nGlobal Context:\nIndia's carbon market follows the model of the EU Emissions Trading System (EU ETS), which has been operational since 2005. China launched its national carbon market in 2021.","",b,A.a(["Government sets emission intensity benchmarks","Industries measure their emissions","Better performers earn CCCs","Underperformers must buy CCCs","Trading happens on Indian Carbon Market","BEE oversees compliance","Emission reduction achieved via market incentive"],b8),"","a7","https://picsum.photos/seed/carbon_trading/800/400",!1,m,B.bW,"CARBON: C=Credit certificates, A=Administrator is BEE, R=Reduction targets 45%, B=Benchmarks for industries, O=On Indian Carbon Market, N=Net-zero 2070 aligned",a2,B.ag,n,l,p,"","India launches its first comprehensive Carbon Credit Trading Scheme (CCTS) regulated by the Bureau of Energy Efficiency to meet Paris Agreement targets.","","Carbon Credit Trading Scheme: India's Market-Based Climate Action",a1)
